  "prompt": "Which is a good solar panel installation provider in San Dimas, California CA?",
  "response": "Finding a \"good\" solar panel installation provider is subjective and depends on your specific needs and priorities. However, here's a breakdown of factors to consider and some highly-rated options in the San Dimas area, along with resources to help you make an informed decision:\n\n**Factors to Consider When Choosing a Solar Installer:**\n\n*   **Reputation and Reviews:** Check online reviews on sites like Yelp, Google Reviews, Better Business Bureau (BBB), and SolarReviews. Pay attention to both the number of reviews and the overall rating.  Look for common themes in the reviews, both positive and negative.\n*   **Experience:** How long has the company been in business? A longer track record often indicates stability and expertise.\n*   **Licensing and Insurance:**  Ensure the company is properly licensed and insured in California.  This protects you in case of accidents or faulty workmanship.  You can verify licenses on the CSLB (California State License Board) website.\n*   **Certifications:** Look for certifications from organizations like NABCEP (North American Board of Certified Energy Practitioners). NABCEP certification signifies a high level of training and expertise.\n*   **Warranty:**  What warranties are offered on the panels, inverters, and workmanship? A good warranty provides peace of mind.  Pay attention to the length and terms of the warranty.\n*   **Price and Financing Options:**  Get multiple quotes and compare prices. Understand the financing options available (e.g., cash purchase, loan, lease, PPA). Consider the long-term cost of ownership.\n*   **Panel and Inverter Brands:**  Research the brands of solar panels and inverters the company offers.  Look for reputable brands with good performance and reliability.\n*   **Customer Service:**  How responsive and helpful is the company during the initial consultation and throughout the installation process?\n*   **Local Knowledge:** A local company will be familiar with local building codes, permitting processes, and net metering policies.\n\n**Potential Solar Installation Providers in or Serving San Dimas, CA (Based on Reviews and Reputation):**\n\n*   **SunPower by Green Convergence:** Often gets high marks for using premium SunPower panels and providing excellent customer service.  SunPower panels are known for their high efficiency and durability.\n*   **Tesla:** If you're interested in Tesla products (panels, Powerwall), they are an option. They can sometimes be competitively priced, but customer service experiences can vary.  Read reviews carefully.\n*   **Titan Solar Power:** National company that often subcontracts installation. Price can be competitive. Be sure to vet the quality of the local subcontractors.\n*   **NRG Clean Power:**  Larger company, often has competitive pricing and financing options.\n*   **ADT Solar (formerly Sunpro Solar):** National company. Read reviews specific to your local area.\n*   **Local Solar Installers:**  Search on Yelp, Google Maps, and SolarReviews for smaller, local companies that might be more responsive and offer personalized service.  Examples might include companies with names like \"[San Dimas] Solar,\" \"[Local Area] Energy,\" etc.\n\n**How to Research and Choose an Installer:**\n\n1.  **Get Multiple Quotes:** Contact at least 3-5 different installers and request detailed quotes.\n2.  **Read Reviews:**  Thoroughly read reviews on multiple platforms (Yelp, Google, BBB, SolarReviews).  Pay attention to trends and patterns in the reviews.\n3.  **Verify Licenses and Insurance:** Check the California State License Board (CSLB) website to verify the contractor's license and insurance.\n4.  **Ask Questions:**  Don't be afraid to ask questions about the company's experience, warranties, financing options, and installation process.\n5.  **Check for NABCEP Certification:**  Ask if the installers are NABCEP certified.\n6.  **Read the Fine Print:**  Carefully review the contract before signing anything.  Pay attention to the terms and conditions, warranties, and payment schedule.\n7.  **Net Metering and Rebates:**  Understand California's net metering policies and any available rebates or incentives.  Your installer should be knowledgeable about these programs.  (Go Solar California website)\n\n**Resources to Help You Find and Evaluate Solar Installers:**\n\n*   **California State License Board (CSLB):**  Verify licenses and check for complaints.  [https://www.cslb.ca.gov/](https://www.cslb.ca.gov/)\n*   **Better Business Bureau (BBB):** Check for complaints and ratings.  [https://www.bbb.org/](https://www.bbb.org/)\n*   **Yelp:**  Read local reviews.\n*   **Google Reviews:**  Read local reviews.\n*   **SolarReviews:**  A website dedicated to solar panel reviews and installer ratings. [https://www.solarreviews.com/](https://www.solarreviews.com/)\n*   **EnergySage:**  An online marketplace where you can compare solar quotes from multiple installers. [https://www.energysage.com/](https://www.energysage.com/)\n*   **Go Solar California:** Information on California's solar programs and incentives. [https://www.gosolarcalifornia.ca.gov/](https://www.gosolarcalifornia.ca.gov/)\n\n**Important Considerations for San Dimas, CA:**\n\n*   **Permitting:**  San Dimas likely has specific permitting requirements for solar installations.  Make sure your installer is familiar with these requirements.\n*   **HOA Restrictions:**  If you live in a homeowners association (HOA), there may be restrictions on solar panel installations.  Check with your HOA before proceeding.\n*   **Net Metering:**  Southern California Edison (SCE) is the utility provider in San Dimas.  Understand SCE's net metering policies.\n\nBy carefully researching your options and considering your specific needs, you can find a good solar panel installation provider in San Dimas, CA. Good luck!\n",
